const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-options', text: 'Visa Options for Digital Nomads', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-plans', text: 'Best Plans for Digital Nomads', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare as a Nomad', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Thailand Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/thailand/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Digital Nomads', href: '/insurance-for/digital-nomads' },
  { title: 'SafetyWing Review', href: '/providers/safetywing' },
  { title: 'IMG Global Review', href: '/providers/img-global' },
  { title: 'Cigna Global in Thailand', href: '/countries/thailand/insurance/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'More in Southeast Asia', href: '/regions/southeast-asia' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'type', header: 'Best For' },
  { key: 'flexibility', header: 'Nomad Flexibility' },
  { key: 'startingPrice', header: 'From' },
];

const planRows = [
  { provider: 'SafetyWing', type: 'Budget nomads', flexibility: 'Excellent', startingPrice: '$45/mo' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', type: 'Mid-range coverage', flexibility: 'Very good', startingPrice: '$85/mo' },
  { provider: 'World Nomads', type: 'Adventure activities', flexibility: 'Good', startingPrice: '$65/mo' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', type: 'Comprehensive coverage', flexibility: 'Moderate', startingPrice: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross', type: 'Thailand-based nomads', flexibility: 'Limited', startingPrice: '$80/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Digital Nomads in Thailand | Expat Insurance Guide"
  description="Find the best health insurance for digital nomads living in Thailand. Compare flexible plans, understand visa requirements, and get coverage that moves with you."
  headline="Health Insurance for Digital Nomads in Thailand"
  subheadline="Coverage that works for the nomad lifestyle—flexible, affordable, and designed for people who don't stay in one place."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/thailand-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Nomad-Friendly Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Thailand has long been a digital nomad hotspot. Chiang Mai consistently ranks as one of the world's best cities for remote work, and Bangkok, Phuket, and Koh Phangan all have thriving nomad communities. The combination of low costs, excellent internet, abundant coworking spaces, and quality healthcare makes it an ideal base.
  </p>
  <p>
    But as a digital nomad, your insurance needs differ from traditional expats. You're likely moving between countries, don't have a fixed address for long, and need coverage that travels with you. Here's what you need to know about getting insured while based in Thailand.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Digital Nomad Insurance Priorities</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li>✓ Coverage in multiple countries without changing plans</li>
      <li>✓ Monthly payment options (not locked into annual contracts)</li>
      <li>✓ Telemedicine for consultations from anywhere</li>
      <li>✓ No fixed address requirements</li>
      <li>✓ Affordable premiums on variable income</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Staying in Thailand?"
    description="Compare plans that work for nomads moving between countries or using Thailand as a base."
    buttonText="See Nomad-Friendly Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="visa-options">Visa Options for Digital Nomads</h2>
  <p>
    Thailand doesn't have a dedicated digital nomad visa yet, but there are several options for remote workers who want to stay legally.
  </p>

  <h3>Long-Term Resident (LTR) Visa — Best Official Option</h3>
  <p>
    The LTR visa includes a "Work-from-Thailand Professional" category specifically for remote workers. Requirements:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Income of at least $80,000/year for the past 2 years</li>
    <li>Employment with a company listed on a stock exchange OR with revenue of $150M+</li>
    <li>Health insurance with $50,000 coverage (or $100,000 deposit instead)</li>
    <li>10-year visa with annual reporting only (no 90-day reports)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The LTR is excellent if you qualify, but the income requirements are high for many nomads.
  </p>

  <h3>Tourist Visa Extensions — Common but Limited</h3>
  <p>
    Most digital nomads enter on visa exemption (30-60 days depending on nationality) or a tourist visa (60 days, extendable to 90). You can extend at immigration offices for 30 days. This works for short stays but requires visa runs for longer periods.
  </p>

  <h3>Education Visa (ED Visa)</h3>
  <p>
    Some nomads study Thai language or Muay Thai to qualify for an education visa, allowing 1-year stays. Grey area for remote work, but commonly used.
  </p>

  <h3>Elite Visa</h3>
  <p>
    A 5-20 year visa for a one-time fee ($15,000-60,000). No work permit, but allows long-term residence. Popular with higher-income nomads wanting stability.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Insurance and Visa Reality</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Only the LTR visa requires proof of health insurance. Tourist visas, ED visas, and Elite visas don't mandate insurance. That said, having coverage is strongly recommended—a hospital stay in Thailand can cost $10,000+ without insurance.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    For most digital nomads using tourist visas or visa runs, there's no legal insurance requirement. However, if you're applying for the LTR visa:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum coverage:</strong> $50,000 USD in medical costs</li>
    <li><strong>Alternative:</strong> Deposit $100,000 USD instead of buying insurance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For tourist visas, you just need to show proof of onward travel and sufficient funds. Insurance isn't checked at the border, but that doesn't mean you should skip it.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-plans">Best Plans for Digital Nomads</h2>
  <p>
    Here are the most popular insurance options for digital nomads in Thailand, evaluated for flexibility, coverage, and nomad-friendliness.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>SafetyWing Nomad Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    The most popular choice for budget-conscious nomads. SafetyWing works on 28-day subscription cycles—you can start and stop anytime. Coverage works in 180+ countries, and you can purchase while already abroad.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$45/month (under 40)</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> $250,000 max, $250 deductible</li>
    <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Flexible, affordable, no commitment, covers home visits</li>
    <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Limited coverage (travel medical, not comprehensive health), no routine care</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nomads on a budget who move frequently and want basic emergency coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>IMG Global Travel Medical</h3>
  <p>
    A step up from SafetyWing with higher limits and more comprehensive coverage. IMG offers plans up to $5M in coverage and includes options for pre-existing conditions (with waiting periods).
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$85-150/month</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Up to $5,000,000</li>
    <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Higher limits, US coverage available, 50% deductible waiver outside US</li>
    <li><strong>Cons:</strong> More expensive than SafetyWing, annual commitment for some plans</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nomads wanting more robust coverage without full expat insurance prices.
  </p>

  <h3>World Nomads</h3>
  <p>
    Popular with adventure travelers. Covers 200+ activities including scuba diving, motorbiking, and rock climbing—activities often excluded by other insurers.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$65-100/month</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> $100,000-$500,000 depending on plan</li>
    <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Adventure sports covered, trip cancellation included, 24/7 assistance</li>
    <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Trip-based rather than ongoing, claims can be slow</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Active nomads who want coverage for motorbiking, diving, or adventure activities.
  </p>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    If you want comprehensive health insurance (not just travel medical), Cigna Global offers full coverage including routine care, mental health, and chronic condition management.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$180-300/month</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> $1M-3M, worldwide</li>
    <li><strong>Pros:</strong> True health insurance, excellent network in Thailand, routine care included</li>
    <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Annual commitment, higher cost, overkill for some nomads</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nomads using Thailand as a long-term base who want comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Find the Right Plan"
    description="Compare coverage, costs, and flexibility for digital nomads."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access">Healthcare as a Nomad in Thailand</h2>
  <p>
    Thailand's healthcare system is excellent for nomads. Private hospitals in Bangkok, Chiang Mai, and Phuket offer world-class care with English-speaking staff.
  </p>

  <h3>Where Nomads Get Care</h3>
  <p>
    Popular hospitals with direct billing and English service:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bangkok:</strong> Bumrungrad, Bangkok Hospital, Samitivej</li>
    <li><strong>Chiang Mai:</strong> Bangkok Hospital Chiang Mai, Chiang Mai Ram</li>
    <li><strong>Phuket:</strong> Bangkok Hospital Phuket, Siriroj Hospital</li>
    <li><strong>Koh Samui:</strong> Bangkok Hospital Samui</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Telemedicine Options</h3>
  <p>
    For minor issues, many insurers offer telemedicine. SafetyWing partners with telemedicine providers for virtual consultations. Cigna Global and Allianz have apps for booking virtual appointments. This is useful when you're in a remote area or don't want to visit a hospital for a minor issue.
  </p>

  <h3>Clinics vs Hospitals</h3>
  <p>
    For minor issues, local clinics are affordable ($20-50) and don't require insurance. Many nomads pay out of pocket for basic care and use insurance only for serious issues. Pharmacies in Thailand also sell many medications without prescription.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Costs</h2>

  <h3>Insurance Costs for Nomads</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Basic travel medical (SafetyWing):</strong> $45-76/month</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-range travel medical (IMG):</strong> $85-150/month</li>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive international:</strong> $150-300/month</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Out-of-Pocket Healthcare Costs</h3>
  <p>
    Thailand is affordable enough that many nomads skip insurance for routine care:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clinic visit:</strong> $20-50</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital outpatient:</strong> $50-100</li>
    <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $30-50</li>
    <li><strong>Pharmacy medications:</strong> $5-30</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The risk is hospitalization—a serious accident or illness can cost $10,000-50,000+. That's why even basic travel medical insurance is worth having.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can I buy insurance while already in Thailand?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. SafetyWing, IMG, and World Nomads all allow you to purchase while abroad. Most plans have a short waiting period (24-72 hours) before coverage starts.
  </p>

  <h3>Is SafetyWing enough for Thailand?</h3>
  <p>
    For most healthy nomads, yes. SafetyWing covers emergencies, hospitalizations, and acute illness. It doesn't cover routine checkups, pre-existing conditions, or dental. If you have ongoing health needs, consider a more comprehensive plan.
  </p>

  <h3>Do I need insurance for a Thai tourist visa?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Tourist visas and visa exemptions don't require insurance. Only the LTR visa requires proof of health coverage ($50,000 minimum).
  </p>

  <h3>What about motorbike accidents?</h3>
  <p>
    This is a big one in Thailand. Most insurance covers motorbike accidents IF you have a valid license (international driving permit with motorcycle endorsement, or Thai license). Without a license, many insurers will deny claims. Check your policy carefully.
  </p>

  <h3>What if I hop between Thailand and other countries?</h3>
  <p>
    Travel medical plans like SafetyWing and IMG cover you in 180+ countries—you don't need to change plans when moving. Just ensure Thailand and your other destinations are included (most countries are, except sometimes the US).
  </p>

  <h3>Should I get Thai local insurance or international?</h3>
  <p>
    If Thailand is your permanent base and you don't travel much, local insurers like Pacific Cross offer good value. If you move between countries regularly, stick with international travel medical or global health insurance for flexibility.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Get Covered?"
    description="Compare nomad-friendly plans that work in Thailand and beyond."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Visa rules change frequently, and working remotely on a tourist visa is technically not permitted in Thailand (though widely done). Consult immigration professionals for legal advice. Insurance coverage varies by provider—always read policy documents carefully.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
